high kinetic energy, just as a tightly confined particle must

54
00:03:14,570 --> 00:03:17,441
have high momentum due to the uncertainty principle.

55
00:03:17,541 --> 00:03:21,202
Finally, the potential energy term V of x times psi represents

56
00:03:21,302 --> 00:03:25,024
the influence of external forces on the particle. This could be

57
00:03:25,124 --> 00:03:28,422
the electric potential from a nucleus in an atom, or the

58
00:03:28,522 --> 00:03:32,244
walls of a quantum box. The potential shapes the allowed energy

59
00:03:32,344 --> 00:03:36,066
states and determines where the particle is likely to be found.

60
00:03:37,166 --> 00:03:41,032
The wave function itself is not directly observable. What we can

61
00:03:41,132 --> 00:03:44,999
measure is the probability of finding a particle at a particular

62
00:03:45,099 --> 00:03:48,655
location. This is given by the square of the absolute value

63
00:03:48,755 --> 00:03:52,374
of the wave function, which we call the probability density.

64
00:03:52,474 --> 00:03:56,160
Here's the beautiful part. Even though the wave function is

65
00:03:56,260 --> 00:04:00,332
complex and can be negative or imaginary, the probability density

66
00:04:00,432 --> 00:04:04,568
is always real and non-negative. This makes physical sense because

67
00:04:04,668 --> 00:04:09,510
probabilities must be positive numbers. The star denotes complex conjugation.

68
00:04:09,607 --> 00:04:13,316
The probability density must integrate to one over all space. This is

69
00:04:13,416 --> 00:04:17,457
called normalization. It means that the particle must be somewhere with one

70
00:04:17,557 --> 00:04:21,377
hundred percent certainty. The shape of this curve tells us where we're

71
00:04:21,477 --> 00:04:24,580
most likely to find the particle if we make a measurement.

72
